    "headline": "Residents Throw Away a Third Less Than 15 Years Ago",
    "lede": "Living in Reykjavík means keeping an eye on the waste bins. But fewer bins and less rubbish are filling up the streets these days. Over the past 15 years, the amount of household waste per person has dropped by about 35%, falling from 266 kg in 1998 to just 173 kg in 2012.",
    "story_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "callout",
        "body": "Since 1998, the amount each resident throws away has dropped by about a third.",
        "highlight_value": "35%",
        "highlight_label": "less waste per person"
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Households Are Using Fewer Bins",
        "body": "In the chart below, you’ll notice the number of waste bins across the city steadily rises to a peak in 2004 and then falls sharply. There were about 47,200 bins in 1998, peaking around 47,900 in 2004. But after that, the number dropped by about a fifth, landing at just over 37,300 bins in 2012. This shows that not only are people throwing away less, but fewer bins are needed for the job.",
        "viz_index": 0
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Big Drop in Waste Per Person After 2000",
        "body": "The next chart shows how much rubbish each person in Reykjavík put out each year. It hit its highest point in 2000 at 273 kg per person, but then dropped sharply. By 2012, that number was down to 173 kg—about a third less than before. This steady decline after 2000 stands out, showing a clear shift toward throwing away less.",
        "viz_index": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "What This Means for Daily Life",
        "body": "For residents, these changes translate to less waste being carried out each week. Fewer bins and lighter loads are a sign that habits are shifting—whether from recycling, reuse, or simply wasting less. All these small efforts together have made a real difference citywide."
      }
    ],
    "data_note": "These numbers cover 1998 to 2012, so changes since then aren’t included. The figures reflect the whole city, not specific neighborhoods. There are some changes in how bins were counted, and some waste collection costs may not be fully reflected for the last year. Reykjavik's environmental and planning department collected this information, but the open data doesn’t list a licence.",
    "followup_question": "How much has the city spent on waste collection over the years?",
